Frequently, disinfectants are saved
More than a thousand infections have been reported in hospitals due to incorrect use of antibiotics.
The hygiene conditions in the hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, the overload of staff - all factors that are not directly conducive to the control of infections, according to the chief doctor of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many places, disinfectants are also saved.
A MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed in the traumatology department of the János Hospital.
The bacterium resistant to antibiotics was found in a male patient who was transferred to the hospital after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection here.
The injured person of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but shortly later the man had to return with a MRSA infection. Since then, an important surgery has not yet been carried out due to the bacteria still in the patient’s body.
By 10 December of this year, 1094 infections caused by multiresistant pathogens from hospitals were reported to the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, according to Karolina Böröcz, the leading physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
So many infections caused by multiresistent pathogens have been recorded in hospitals with certainty, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
About two thirds of the infections (683 cases) were triggered by MRSA, which is resistant to methicillin-oxacillin Staphylococcus aureus.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacterium bears about one third of the people in their nose without causing a disease.
SA-related infections (such as throat inflammation, mantle inflammation, skin inflammation or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well healable.
However, if the medicines are too high doses or are used incorrectly, antibiotic-resistant bacteria, which are rapidly spreading in hospitals under appropriate conditions, are produced from the well-responsive bacteria.
Especially in patients with weakened immune system, or permanently poor, but also in elderly, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria may cause serious infections such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents belong to the hospital everyday.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi - MRSA said that there is only no place where it is not sought.
Resistent to antibiotics
"Such patients are isolated, the nurses wear rubber gloves and masks in the care, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment" - Tibor Nyulasi says.
While patients are being studied for MRSA when they are sent to the hospital, infection cannot be avoided.
Too rare sampling
The majority of the infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the conditions and circumstances currently prevailing are unfavourable for the control of the emergence or spread of the multiresistent pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection is predominantly occurring in hospitals and old-age homes, the meals should examine the patients received and insulate MRSA infected immediately.
In the Hungarian hospitals, however, microbiological sampling is not practiced as often.
Not least because there are no grants from the public health insurance fund for this investigation.
Most cases would therefore only come to the light of the day when the patient already has a noticeable MRSA infection, according to the medical head of the epidemiology centre.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and disease images.
Antimicrobial therapy is intended to be targeted, i.e. microbiological studies are necessary in order not to create resistance to the medicine, but this directive is not always complied with by hospitals.
Among the ambulances, or in primary care patients, microbiological samples are even more rare, says Karolina Böröcz.
Saved for disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most commonly transferred from one patient to another by the nurse.
This is why handwashing or wearing gloves and masks is of great importance, but there are also significant deficiencies in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in the local hospitals there is not always the possibility of isolating the infected patients.
The rooms are often overfilled, the beds are close to each other, although from an epidemiological point of view there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately, it is even in the less well-funded hospitals that disinfectants are saved, there are few nurses, many patients - all factors that directly promote the formation of infections.
Such infections are proven to be far less frequent there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are observed, says Karolina Böröcz.
Government programme against MRSA
To control MRSA infections causes huge costs to health insurance, so they are fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA and its control were maintained in the government programme.
After first signs, the program is successful - as published data prove, the trend of MRSA infections in England is declining.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has declared the prevention of the formation of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals one of its priorities.
