Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
As Minister for the Environment Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will be continued by ministers on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries discuss the Bali roadmap, which sets out emissions reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the Kyoto Protocol.
There is currently a strong debate between industrialised and developing countries.
The United States has already signaled that they do not want to negotiate concrete figures, but they would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 per cent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major question of the conference is whether the industrialised countries are willing to support developing countries, in addition to reducing emissions, both financially and technologically.
An agreement has also been reached on support for developing countries.
The adaptation fund under the Kyoto Protocol is to be managed by a 16-member Council, which is expected to be read in the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), as described in the Piac ets Profit.
Hungary's six percent
On behalf of Hungary, Minister for the Environment Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its leading role in global climate protection measures and to achieve a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister stated that by 2020 the EU will reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% (measured at 1990 values), whether or not the "accord after 2012" will be successful or not. The Union would even be willing to make a 30% reduction, provided that other major industrialised countries in the world, or developing countries are also willing to fulfil their obligations in terms of strength and responsibility.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the objective of the States which had joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2 per cent, while the EU had already committed itself to a reduction of 8% with its 15 Member States at the time.
The target for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985-87 - a requirement that the country will fully fulfil, as is to be read in the Ministry of the Environment's press release.
The effort is high on Bali - after all, the long-term international climate policy agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly only enter into force after 2012. In this case, the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a new international emission reduction system, whose importance has also been highlighted by the IPCC, the International Scientific Committee on Climate Change, with the Nobel Peace Prize, in its recent report.
This would delay the emission reduction, and increasing the average temperature of the earth by more than 2°C would be inevitable, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
