In Hungary, holidays are strictly regulated by law, so that the practice of redistributing the working days around the holidays has now been established, but in the coming year we have less such days.
In the EU and in America, one also understands something else as "February Day".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and free working days.
Working-free days are mostly church holidays, or are related to important historical events.
For example, we are also celebrating New Year: both the last day of the old and the first day of the new year are working-free days - the latter is the only way that the New Year's Celebrations can rest.
Throughout the year we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The state celebrations are the 15th of March, which reminds of the revolution of 1848, and the 23rd of October, the commemorative day of the revolution of 1956.
On August 20th, the state creation, on May 1st, is celebrated, on November 1 and 2th, we remember our dead.
In addition, there are every two holidays to Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our public, national or religious holidays rarely fall to a weekend, the practice of "working day shift" has proved to be proven in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
However, the price of extended weekends is that we have to work very well on Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is finally finalised, the Minister of Labour has for many years been set up in its own regulation.
The legislation applies equally to all employers and workers, public servants and public service officials.
Except only companies and facilities where the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on holidays.
It is only the holidays at the end of the year that make the working order a little mess: from 24 December, life remains formal for this purpose, since most of the days between Christmas and New Year's Equilibrium, or take the holidays which have been revoked for it.
Next year, more holidays fall in the middle of the week, or at the end of the week, so that there will be less redispositions in the working days than this year.
The calendar is first placed around the day of work, so that people can stay at home for four days.
Saturday, April 26th will be a working day so that Friday, May 2, can be a rest day.
The second redisposition is related to the holiday on October 23: Saturday, October 18, you will have to finish Friday, October 24.
However, the end of the year will remain in the sign of the holidays, after 24 December everything will be lying and standing, even if New Year's Day falls to a Wednesday.
