In addition to modernising financial markets, the MIFID, which re-establishes the Securities Services Regulation, seeks to improve investor protection, increase the Spanish Securities Commission's (CNMV) control claim and promote cooperation between the various supervisory authorities of the European Union.
The new Directive enables both specialized companies and natural or legal persons to provide financial advice and also contributes to the establishment of new financial services companies (ESIS) to consulting companies joining investment and intermediary companies in securities.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the execution of financial transactions, so that the regulated market markets will be added to the multilateral systems of securities business and to the systems of internationalisation of trade orders, which would finally compete with the current economic operators.
The Act obliges investment companies to report the focus of their corporate profile, confrontation and the forms of dealing with risks on the market and to register all projects carried out in order to facilitate CNMV's control tasks.
