A new price dispute between Ukraine and Russia increased the risk that Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe would be affected.
The majority of Russian natural gas exports to the European Union (EU) is led by Ukraine and any dispute between the two nations is monitored very closely.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for gas, Russia will charge higher transit charges.
An earlier conflict between the two countries last year reduced deliveries to the EU countries.
The recent dispute between Kiev and Moscow occurs at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian gas monopoly Gazprom attempt to reach agreement on how much Ukraine has to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine needs to be calculated more, as the Group has agreed to pay up to 50% more for natural gas from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine has to pay 40% more for imports of Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in discussions," said the Ukrainian Minister for Economic Affairs Anatoli Kinakh of Reuters News Agency.
"The changing natural gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit fees [to Western Europe] through Ukraine."
In the last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom shortened supplies to Ukraine.
This resulted in a case of exports to Western Europe, which led to a drastic increase in prices.
Russian gas accounts for one quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the world's largest gas reserves, but much of them remain underdeveloped.
The result is that Gazprom supplements its own stocks with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
