An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 - with Warhol's consent - produced hundreds of Brillo boxes from cardboard: these came (for cost reasons) not from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo carton factory.
It was not artwork, it was their models, it was just exhibition pieces.
At the same time, Warhol probably granted permission in 1968 to produce a few Brillo wooden cushions in Sweden, but they were not issued at the Moderna Museum.
Contemporary witnesses now speak of about fifteen boxes, which were rightly entered into the art and auction history as authorized original Andy Warhol-Brillo boxes with the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have earned more than $100 000 on auctions.
The problem is now that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that it had been produced and exhibited about a hundred wooden boxes in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 boxes were produced in Malmö for an exhibition in St. Petersburg only in 1990.
At that time Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, Chefkonservator at the Moderna Museet, has also investigated three Swedish private-owned Brillo-Boxes, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their press panels were only founded and molded, and then white oil colour was applied with a brush.
On the other hand, the structure of the copies from 1990 reveals that the colour has been applied directly to the press panel with a painter roll without foundation - and it is not oil, but acrylic.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes," says Lars Nittve, director of Moderna Museet: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come to another conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six boxes in its collection as copies/exposure material."
